╭─ Assistant [MainThread@2559895] ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
│ I've analyzed the bug report and the test failures. The root cause is that                 │
│ `LoopPredication` attempts to widen a loop guard condition using a SCEV expression that is │
│ not available at the loop's entry, leading to an assertion failure in                      │
│ `ScalarEvolution::isLoopEntryGuardedByCond`.                                               │
│                                                                                            │
│ The problematic value is `%length`, which is loaded in an outer loop. While it is          │
│ invariant with respect to the inner loop (`%loop1`), it is not available at its entry      │
│ because the `load` instruction does not dominate the inner loop's preheader.               │
│                                                                                            │
│ My proposed fix is to add a check in                                                       │
│ `LoopPredication::widenICmpRangeCheckIncrementingLoop` to ensure that the SCEV for the     │
│ guard's limit is available at the loop entry before attempting to use it for widening.     │
│ This prevents the pass from making an invalid assumption that leads to the crash.          │
│                                                                                            │
│ I will now apply this fix.                                                                 │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```patch                                                                                   │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/LoopPredication.cpp                                       │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/LoopPredication.cpp                                       │
│ @@ -552,6 +552,12 @@                                                                       │
│    const SCEV *GuardLimit = RangeCheck.Limit;                                              │
│    const SCEV *LatchStart = LatchCheck.IV->getStart();                                     │
│    const SCEV *LatchLimit = LatchCheck.Limit;                                              │
│ +                                                                                          │
│ +  if (!SE->isAvailableAtLoopEntry(GuardLimit, L)) {                                       │
│ +    LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Guard limit is not available at loop entry!\n");                │
│ +    return std::nullopt;                                                                  │
│ +  }                                                                                       │
│ +                                                                                          │
│    // Subtlety: We need all the values to be *invariant* across all iterations,            │
│    // but we only need to check expansion safety for those which *aren't*                  │
│    // already guaranteed to dominate the guard.                                            │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```                                                                                        │
