│ I have analyzed the bug and the repeated test failures. The core issue is that             │
│ `LoopPredication` is making an incorrect assumption about the availability of a SCEV       │
│ expression. The expression for the loop guard's limit (`%length.lcssa`) is loop-invariant  │
│ with respect to the inner loop, but its defining value is not available at the loop's      │
│ entry, which causes an assertion failure in `ScalarEvolution`.                             │
│                                                                                            │
│ My previous attempts to fix this by adding checks were on the right track but were either  │
│ placed incorrectly or were too restrictive, causing a legitimate test case to fail. The    │
│ test case fails because the transformation is being prevented, but the test expects it to  │
│ occur. This suggests that simply disabling the transformation is not the correct fix.      │
│                                                                                            │
│ The correct fix is to ensure that all SCEV components used to build the widened check are  │
│ available at the loop entry *before* they are used. The existing `isLoopInvariantValue`    │
│ check is insufficient because it only checks for loop invariance, not availability at the  │
│ loop entry.                                                                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ I will replace the `isLoopInvariantValue` checks with `SE->isAvailableAtLoopEntry`. This   │
│ is a more precise check that correctly identifies SCEV expressions that are safe to use.   │
│ This change should be made in both `widenICmpRangeCheckIncrementingLoop` and               │
│ `widenICmpRangeCheckDecrementingLoop` for consistency. This will fix the assertion without │
│ being overly conservative and should allow the test case to pass.                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```patch                                                                                   │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/LoopPredication.cpp                                       │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/LoopPredication.cpp                                       │
│ @@ -555,10 +555,10 @@                                                                      │
│    // Subtlety: We need all the values to be *invariant* across all iterations,            │
│    // but we only need to check expansion safety for those which *aren't*                  │
│    // already guaranteed to dominate the guard.                                            │
│ -  if (!isLoopInvariantValue(GuardStart) ||                                                │
│ -      !isLoopInvariantValue(GuardLimit) ||                                                │
│ -      !isLoopInvariantValue(LatchStart) ||                                                │
│ -      !isLoopInvariantValue(LatchLimit)) {                                                │
│ +  if (!SE->isAvailableAtLoopEntry(GuardStart, L) ||                                       │
│ +      !SE->isAvailableAtLoopEntry(GuardLimit, L) ||                                       │
│ +      !SE->isAvailableAtLoopEntry(LatchStart, L) ||                                       │
│ +      !SE->isAvailableAtLoopEntry(LatchLimit, L)) {                                       │
│      LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Can't expand limit check!\n");                                  │
│      return std::nullopt;                                                                  │
│    }                                                                                       │
│ @@ -599,10 +599,10 @@                                                                      │
│    // Subtlety: We need all the values to be *invariant* across all iterations,            │
